South Carolinian employees stated that MycoWorks' executives, including Scullin, Wang, Ross, and Lahoti, deliberately concealed the failing financial situation of the company from employees, stakeholders, and investors, for up to six months prior to the closure, and did not address unsustainable unnecessary expenses. Following the closure, an initial strategy proposed by MycoWorks C-suite executives was to pursue a merger with competitor Ecovative. This did not come to fruition.
South Carolinian employees stated that MycoWorks' executives and certain board members, including Scullin, Wang, Ross, and Lahoti, deliberately concealed the failing financial situation of the company from employees, stakeholders, and investors, for up to six months prior to the closure, and, additionally, did not address unsustainable unnecessary expenses. Following the closure, an initial strategy proposed by MycoWorks C-suite executives was to pursue a merger with competitor Ecovative. This did not come to fruition.


The company entered into insolvency in late October 2025 and chose liquidation via an Assignment for the Benefit of Creditor (ABC) process, in which company assets were first assigned to a newly created company, Mycoworks Liquidation, LLC, and then auctioned off to pay creditors. IP assets were accquired by Daniel Frydenlund of Stage Fund, a Denver-based private equity fund specializing in distressed assets, which formed a new company, Mycoworks Denver, LLC. All other assets remain unassigned, and Mycoworks, Inc has ceased to exist.

Palliser was of English birth, his grandfather, John Palliser, [[Esquire]], being of [[Newby Wiske|Newby-super-Wiske]], [[Yorkshire]]. He was baptised at [[Kirby Wiske]] on 28 July 1644, the son of John Palliser.<ref name="Parish Register">Parish Register</ref> He was educated at Northallerton Grammar School <ref>Dictionary of National Biography</ref> but his father had died before he entered [[Trinity College Dublin]] in 1660.<ref>Alumni Dublinenses</ref>


In 1668, he was elected a [[Fellow]] of Trinity, and in November 1669 he was ordained a [[deacon]] of the [[Church of Ireland]]. On 28 January he was ordained to the [[priest]]hood in [[St Patrick's Cathedral, Dublin]]. In October 1670 Palliser was elected as ''medicus'' of Trinity and in 1678 was appointed as professor of divinity. He gave the [[Latin]] oration at the funeral of [[James Margetson|Archbishop James Margetson]] of Armagh in September 1678.<ref name=palliser>[http://www.palliser.co.uk/archbishop.htm PALLISER, WILLIAM (1646-1727)] at palliser.co.uk</ref>
In 1668, he was elected a [[Fellow]] of Trinity, and in November 1669 he was ordained a [[deacon]] of the [[Church of Ireland]]. On 28 January he was ordained to the [[priest]]hood in [[St Patrick's Cathedral, Dublin]]. In October 1670 Palliser was elected as ''medicus'' of Trinity and in 1678 was appointed as professor of divinity. He gave the [[Latin]] oration at the funeral of [[James Margetson|Archbishop James Margetson]] of Armagh in September 1678.<ref name=palliser>[https://www.palliser.co.uk/archbishop.htm PALLISER, WILLIAM (1646-1727)] at palliser.co.uk</ref>


On 14 February 1692/93, a year after the [[battle of the Boyne]], appointed on 14 February 1692/3, Palliser was consecrated Bishop of Cloyne. On 10 April 1694 he was nominated as Archbishop of Cashel, this appointment being confirmed by [[letters patent]] dated 26 June 1694. After his translation he held the see until his death on 1 January 1726/27.<ref name=palliser/> He was buried in January 1726/7, at St. Andrew's in Dublin.<ref name="Parish Register"/>

On 10 April 1694 he was nominated as Archbishop of Cashel, this appointment being confirmed by [[letters patent]] dated 26 June 1694. After his translation he held the see until his death on 1 January 1726/27.<ref name=palliser/> He was buried in January 1726/7, at St. Andrew's in Dublin.<ref name="Parish Register"/>

Emelda Modi hailed from [[Akobo County]].<ref name=post/> Emelda Modi was appointed member of the [[National Assembly of Sudan]] by presidential decree in August 2005.<ref>{{cite web|website=Sudaress|url=https://www.sudaress.com/smc/830|title=مرسوم جمهوري رقم (24) بتخصيص مقاعد المجلس الوطني في الهيئة التشريعية القومية|date=January 27, 2008}}</ref> She stood as a National Assembly candidate on the [[Sudan People's Liberation Movement]] (SPLM) women's list in [[Jonglei State]] in the [[2010 Sudanese general election in Jonglei|2010 elections]], and was elected.<ref>National Election Commission. In May 2021 she was appointed to the [[Reconstituted Transitional National Legislative Assembly]], as a SPLM representative.<ref>{{cite web|website=Talk of Juba|url=https://www.talkofjuba.com/2021/05/members-of-the-parliament-of-south-sudan/|title=Members of the Parliament of South Sudan|author=Mariak Bol|date=May 19, 2021}}</ref>
In May 2021 she was appointed to the [[National Legislative Assembly|Reconstituted Transitional National Legislative Assembly]], as a SPLM representative.<ref>{{cite web|website=Talk of Juba|url=https://www.talkofjuba.com/2021/05/members-of-the-parliament-of-south-sudan/|title=Members of the Parliament of South Sudan|author=Mariak Bol|date=May 19, 2021}}</ref> She died on June 22, 2021 in Khartoum, at the age of 57.<ref name=post>{{cite web|url=https://www.sudanspost.com/south-sudan-lawmaker-dies-in-khartoum/|website=Sudans Post|title=South Sudan lawmaker dies in Khartoum|date=June 26, 2021</ref>

The '''Kunsthalle Zürich''' is a [[kunsthalle]] (a contemporary art exhibition centre) in [[Zürich]], [[Switzerland]].<ref>[http://www.lonelyplanet.com/switzerland/zurich/sights/art-gallery/kunsthalle-zurich Kunsthalle Zürich], [[Lonely Planet]].</ref> Founded in 1985, it is located on Limmatstrasse, near the city centre.<ref>[http://kunsthallezurich.ch/en/information Information] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210310024923/http://kunsthallezurich.ch/en/information |date=2021-03-10 }}, Kunsthalle Zürich, Switzerland.</ref> A number of temporary exhibitions are organized each year.<ref>[http://kunsthallezurich.ch/en/exhibitions#exhibitions_all Past Exhibitions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210305092955/http://kunsthallezurich.ch/en/exhibitions#exhibitions_all |date=2021-03-05 }}, Kunsthalle Zürich, Switzerland.</ref>

'''Frederick William Burwell''' (20 May 1846 – 25 October 1915) was a Scottish architect, who was active in New Zealand and Australia from the 1870s to 1900s. He was the designer of a number of notable buildings in Invercargill, in the South Island of New Zealand, and Fremantle, in Western Australia.
'''Frederick William Burwell''' (20 May 1846 – 25 October 1915) was a Scottish-born [[architect]], who was active in New Zealand and Australia from the 1870s to 1900s. He was the designer of a number of notable buildings in [[Invercargill]], in the [[South Island]] of New Zealand, and [[Fremantle]], in [[Western Australia]].
